    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that a dynamic framework makes the law arbitrary ignores that \"living constitutionalism\" theorists do not advocate for pure judicial whim. Rather, they argue that core principles should remain constant while applying them to modern contexts, providing a tether to underlying values. From an intellectually honest standpoint, originalists argue that adherence to the text is the only true barrier against the judiciary becoming an unchecked political actor. However, others argue that the law *must* evolve if it is to remain relevant and just in a changing society.",
      "source": "target",
